s":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"charlotte-webb-1869"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{"INST026":{"id":"INST026","primary_name":"Philadelphia Female Anti-Slavery Society","name":"Philadelphia Female Anti-Slavery Society","alt_names":[],"type":"abolitionist_organization","founding_year":1833,"location":{"city":"Philadelphia","state":"Pennsylvania"},"wikipedia_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philadelphia_Female_Anti-Slavery_Society","primary_persons":["X00621","HD1915","HD1930","X00634"],"hooker_connected_people":["HD1915","HD1930"],"person_ids":["X00621","X00634"],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Founded 1833 — among the earliest interracial abolitionist organizations in the US. Hester \"Hetty\" Elizabeth Emery Burr (X00621) — wife of John Pierre Burr (HD1915), 6th-generation Hooker descendant — was a member of the Society and participated in the Women's Anti-Slavery Conventions of 1838 and 1839. Charlotte Forten's paternal aunts (Margaretta Forten, Sarah Louisa Forten Purvis, Harriet Forten Purvis) and her grandmother Charlotte Vandine Forten were founding members of the Society. Charlotte Forten herself (connected to the Hooker tree through her aunt Annie Wood's marriage to John G. Webb HD1930) was deeply embedded in this network. Hetty Emery Burr also co-founded the Moral Reform Retreat — Philadelphia's first shelter for African American women. The Society connected the Hooker-Burr abolitionist network with the Forten-Purvis-Grimké abolitionist network that dominated Philadelphia Black civic life for three generations.\n[hooker_connection] co-founded by wives and in-laws of Hooker tree members"}},"crossConnections":[]}